You're right; my mistake. Event subscriptions to Unity Input System actions are commonly done in `Awake()` or `OnEnable()` depending on when you want to start listening to the events and when the Input System is set up.

The reason to consider `OnEnable()` and `OnDisable()` is for robustness around the object activation lifecycle. If the GameObject that the script is attached to gets disabled and then enabled again during the gameplay, you would want to re-subscribe to the input actions upon re-enabling to ensure they keep working.

Subscribing in `Awake()` means the subscriptions will occur as the object is being initialized, which is just once when the object is created or loaded. If your script should only subscribe once and the GameObject is not going to be enabled/disabled during the game, then `Awake()` is suitable. On the other hand, if the GameObject may be enabled/disabled, then `OnEnable()`/`OnDisable()` ensure the script always listens to input actions appropriately while it is active.

Here's an updated approach using `Awake()`:

```csharp
